Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The existing literature on fairness in federated learning (FL) has made significant strides—FairFed introduces server-side fairness-aware aggregation, FedGCR emphasizes group customization for distinct client types, and mFairFL tackles multi-dimensional fairness via gradient conflict resolution. However, a critical gap remains: these methods often assume static or heuristic weight adjustments during model aggregation, failing to dynamically respond to evolving misalignments between local and global fairness objectives. In heterogeneous FL settings—especially where sensitive attributes are distributed unevenly across clients—the local models may optimize for fairness within their own demographic slices while drifting from the global fairness goal. This misalignment can amplify systemic bias over communication rounds. My intuition is that fairness should not be enforced through fixed reweighting or one-time customization but should emerge from a continuous alignment process. Inspired by gradient-based meta-learning and fairness gradients, I propose a novel mechanism that computes a "fairness gradient discrepancy" between local updates and the global fairness direction, then uses this signal to dynamically adjust client aggregation weights. This enables the server to prioritize clients whose update directions contribute most to reducing global group fairness disparity, even if their raw model performance is suboptimal. Unlike prior work, this method does not require access to sensitive attributes at the server (only local proxies), is compatible with various local debiasing strategies, and adapts over time. It uniquely bridges dynamic weight adjustment with *directional fairness alignment*, offering a principled, adaptive solution to collaborative group fairness.

