  "Idea": "This paper proposes 'Layer-Aware Group-Adaptive Fair Aggregation' (LAGFA), a novel federated learning framework designed to achieve group fairness through hierarchical, multi-scale adjustment of aggregation weights based on both layer-specific fairness sensitivity and client group dynamics. LAGFA addresses two critical limitations in existing fairness-aware FL methods: (1) the assumption that fairness degradation affects all model layers uniformly, and (2) the neglect of latent client group structures that amplify systemic bias. The core innovation lies in decomposing the fairness alignment problem into a layered and grouped optimization process. At each communication round, the server first infers latent client groups using differentially private clustering of model update trajectories—capturing institutions or demographics with shared bias patterns—without accessing raw data or explicit attributes. Then, for each layer of the global model, LAGFA computes a 'fairness sensitivity score' by measuring the correlation between local gradient directions and changes in group-wise performance metrics (e.g., true positive rate gaps) estimated via lightweight shadow probes. Layers with high sensitivity (e.g., middle representation layers prone to biased embeddings) are prioritized for fairness-constrained aggregation. For each client group and layer, the server calculates a 'fairness contribution index' (FCI) based on the cosine similarity between the client's layer-wise update and an ideal fairness-preserving direction derived from consensus among well-performing groups. Aggregation weights are then dynamically assigned per layer and per group using a temperature-scaled softmax over FCIs, enabling the global model to selectively integrate updates that improve fairness in vulnerable layers. Crucially, this allows clients who harm fairness in early layers but help in later ones to still contribute beneficially where appropriate. LAGFA integrates seamlessly with any local training procedure and can be stacked atop methods like FedGCR or mFairFL as a meta-controller for fairness. Its design ensures minimal overhead by reusing gradient computations and operating on model deltas only. Potential impact includes enabling fine-grained fairness governance in real-world FL deployments such as credit scoring across banks or diagnostic AI across clinics, where both institutional grouping and architectural bias propagation must be jointly addressed. By introducing layer- and group-aware weight modulation, LAGFA moves beyond scalar weighting schemes toward a structured, anatomy-informed approach to collaborative fairness.",
